posts.name: Ayush Sagar
posts.cooked: Are there any extensions (besides the WPiLib extension) that are useful when writing code for FRC?

posts.name: SLAB-Mr.Thomas
posts.cooked:
A team mate posted yesterday his coding error that caused 30 minutes of debugging time that SonarLint would have caught so I’m trying out that one.

I like good spelling but don’t do it so well so I’m using Code Spell Checker .

posts.name: gcschmit
posts.cooked:
Our extensions.json file is the project’s .vscode folder contains the following:

The extensions.json file is convenient as it ensure each VS Code installation is reminded to install these extensions when opening the project. @SLAB-Mr.Thomas mentioned the last two. We find spotless quite helpful as it ensures all files are formatted consistently. This not only helps with readability but reduces the number of merge conflicts when using GitHub. There is more information about spotless in the wpilib docs .

posts.name: blu28
posts.cooked:
Our team has been working on a Github repo to use as a template. It is in the early stages, but we did create a VSCode extension pack for the extensions we use:

posts.name: Dkt01
posts.cooked: +1 for code spell checker.  Most of the rest of our recommended extensions are focused on formatting and documentation.

InteliJ is nice too if you’re using Java and can afford to use it or get a license and has a FRC plugin

(Not related but a good plug for exploring out of VSCode)

posts.name: Davo
posts.cooked:
nstrike:

InteliJ is nice too if you’re using Java and can afford to use it or get a license

No need to pay for IntelliJ if you’re a student or teacher:

Learn or teach how to code with best-of-industry tools from JetBrains. Free Educational Licenses for JetBrains' tools.

Although IntelliJ Community Edition would be enough too for Java.

I would assume that but unfortunately its a huge pain to setup if you don’t have a .edu email if teams or students are able to get it they should absolutely use it! The other thing us the licenses are free for a year (i think) but community edition is more than enough for most students.

posts.name: Davo
posts.cooked:
nstrike:

the licenses are free for a year

The education licenses can be renewed each year. From that page:

May be renewed free of charge as long as you are a student or a teacher.
